<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="301">
Worker diagnosis. Similar to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:37337" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Tetraponera" genus.bestMatchDistance="418" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Tetraponera grandidieri (Forel)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="301" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grandidieri">T. grandidieri</taxonomicName>
(q.v.), but larger on average. Basal margin of mandible lacking tooth; anterior clypeal margin broadly convex and crenulate, directed forward; metanotal spiracle visible in lateral view of mesosoma; dorsal face of propodeum broadly convex in posterior view; standing pilosity and appressed pubescence generally sparse; integument mostly sublucid, with fine coriarious /puncticulate sculpture; mesosoma, petiole and postpetiole orange-brown, head and gaster a contrasting blackish brown, legs with a black band on the distal portions of the femora.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="301">
Comments. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:261542" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Tetraponera" genus.bestMatchDistance="458" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Tetraponera variegata" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="301" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variegata">T. variegata</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from related species by the bicolored body and black banded legs (Fig. 22). 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:37337" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Tetraponera" genus.bestMatchDistance="294" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Tetraponera grandidieri (Forel)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="301" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grandidieri">T. grandidieri</taxonomicName>
lacks black banding on the legs and, although the body is often bicolored, only the head is dark, not the head and gaster (as in 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:261542" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Tetraponera" genus.bestMatchDistance="513" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Tetraponera variegata" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="301" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variegata">T. variegata</taxonomicName>
). Although such color differences might appear to be a weak basis for treating 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:261542" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Tetraponera" genus.bestMatchDistance="531" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Tetraponera variegata" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="301" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variegata">T. variegata</taxonomicName>
as a species distinct from 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:37337" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Tetraponera" genus.bestMatchDistance="236" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Tetraponera grandidieri (Forel)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="301" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grandidieri">T. grandidieri</taxonomicName>
, the two forms have been collected sympatrically at several sites (PN Marojejy, PN Ranomafana, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Forêt">Foret</normalizedToken>
Ivohibe) without showing any signs of intergradation. One other species, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:260972" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Tetraponera" genus.bestMatchDistance="6284" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Tetraponera hespera WArd" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="301" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hespera">T. hespera</taxonomicName>
, from northwestern Madagascar, exhibits black leg banding in most populations but in that species the body is unicolored light yellow or orange-brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="301">
I have designated a 
<typeStatus>lectotype</typeStatus>
for 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:261542" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Tetraponera" genus.bestMatchDistance="608" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Tetraponera variegata" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="301" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variegata">T. variegata</taxonomicName>
since there is a dealate queen in 
<collectionCode collectionName="Switzerland, Basel, Naturhistorisches Museum">NHMB</collectionCode>
(Basel) from Moramanga (leg. Descarpentries) labeled, incorrectly, as a 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:261542" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Tetraponera" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Tetraponera variegata" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="301" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variegata">variegata</taxonomicName>
&quot;type&quot;. This specimen has no status as a type, but it reflects the practice of earlier myrmecologists of designating &quot;type specimens&quot; for queens and maies when they were described later than the worker caste of the same species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="301">
Distribution and biology. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:261542" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Tetraponera" genus.bestMatchDistance="685" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Tetraponera variegata" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="301" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variegata">T. variegata</taxonomicName>
is known from several widely scattered locations in the rainforest zone of eastern Madagascar (Fig. 24). Its range broadly overlaps the distributions of Г. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:37337" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Tetraponera" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Tetraponera grandidieri (Forel)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="301" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="grandidieri">
grandidieri, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:260975" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Tetraponera" genus.bestMatchDistance="4700" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Tetraponera inermis Ward" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="301" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inermis">T. inermis</taxonomicName>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:260977" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Tetraponera" genus.bestMatchDistance="2449" genus.bestMatchVote="2" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Tetraponera merita Ward" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="301" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="merita">T. merita</taxonomicName>
. Specimens have been collected in Malaise traps and foraging on vegetation. Up to this point no nests have been found.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
